      "content": "You are a subagent tasked with a deep study of GSD workflow patterns and OMO (oh-my-openagent) architecture for the Hivemind project. This study will guide a comprehensive rewrite of ALL hm-* orchestration skills.\n\n**IMPORTANT:** You are a subagent. You must complete this study and return a structured synthesis report. Do NOT implement any code changes — this is research only.\n\n## Context\n\nHivemind is a **runtime composition engine** (npm package) for OpenCode. It provides tools, hooks, and a plugin for delegated session orchestration. The GSD framework and OMO architecture are reference patterns — Phase 23 must TRANSFORM them to Hivemind conventions, NOT copy them.\n\n## Study Resources\n\n1. Read `repo-for-learning-and-synthesis.md` at project root — this is the PRIMARY reference for which patterns to adopt and how to transform them.\n\n2. Read the OMO reference skill at `.opencode/skills/hm-l3-omo-reference/SKILL.md` — this contains OMO architecture patterns.\n\n3. Read the awesome-opencode directory at the path referenced in repo-for-learning-and-synthesis.md — explore OpenCode ecosystem projects for tool/agent patterns.\n\n4. Read `.opencode/skills/hivemind-power-on/SKILL.md` — this is the foundation skill that needs rewriting.\n\n5. Read `.opencode/skills/hm-l2-coordinating-loop/SKILL.md` — example of a coordination skill that needs rewriting.\n\n6. Check if `.opencode/skills/hm-l2-gate-orchestrator/SKILL.md` and `.opencode/skills/hm-l2-completion-looping/SKILL.md` exist and read them.\n\n7. Read `.planning/codebase/ARCHITECTURE.md` — understand CQRS model, 9-surface authority, Hivemind architecture rules.\n\n8. Read `.planning/architecture/hivemind-runtime-identity-taxonomy-2026-05-07.md` — understand Hivemind naming and lineage conventions.\n\n9. Read `.planning/architecture/hivemind-source-plane-architecture-2026-05-07.md` — understand surface ownership model.\n\n## What to Analyze\n\nFor EACH pattern/skill you find, analyze:\n\n1. **What pattern does it use?** (e.g., gate orchestration, phase loop, completion detection)\n2. **What tools does it reference?** Do those tools actually exist?\n3. **What's aspirational vs real?** Flag anything that references non-existent files/tools/scripts.\n4. **Jump links and progressive disclosure** — CRITICAL: Check if the skill uses markdown links to reference other skills, and whether those links actually work (point to existing files at valid paths). User reports that jump links and progressive disclosure mechanisms do NOT work in loaded skills at runtime. Document actual verifiable behavior.\n5. **Context budget efficiency** — How many lines/tokens is the skill? Could it be thinner by using references?\n\n## Output Format\n\nReturn a structured synthesis report containing:\n\n```markdown\n# GSD/OMO Pattern Synthesis for Hivemind Phase 23\n\n## Patterns to ADOPT (with Hivemind transformation)\n- Pattern name | Source (GSD/OMO) | Hivemind transformation | Priority\n\n## Patterns to REJECT\n- Pattern name | Source | Why rejected\n\n## Tool Reference Truth Table\n| Tool/Script Name | Claimed in skill | Actually exists? | File:Line |\n\n## Jump Link/Progressive Disclosure Audit\n| Skill | Link | Target | Actually works? |\n\n## Skill Context Budget Report\n| Skill | Lines | Tokens (est) | Can be thinner? | How? |\n\n## Recommendations for Hivemind Skill Architecture\n- Structural recommendations\n- Loading/caching strategy\n- Conditional loading rules\n```\n\nBe honest and thorough. If a tool or script doesn't exist, say so. If a link is broken, report it. This audit feeds directly into the skill rewrite execution wave.\n",
